We have a new opportunity provided to us by our kitchen this year regarding birthday treats that we wanted to share with you. Note: Birthday treats are not required for your child. We work to make your child's birthday while in school special for them as we know its importance whether treats are involved or not.

The kitchen is offering the opportunity for parents/guardians to order treats for the classroom, if you so choose. All treats for the classroom must follow Akron-Westfield's Healthy Snack Policy, and all items offered are in accordance with guidelines. We ask that you order and pay for items at least 1 week in advance.

Please see the attached pictures for pricing information. Order forms and this same information were emailed to parent addresses on file. Again, this is not required, and is purely optional as a service to families.

Tonight's home football game against the Gehlen Catholic Jays will be live streamed by Fuller Digital Solutions. The link is below.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qFVKMgVX3Xk

Please note that we will be requiring face masks in order to enter through the ticket gate.

Students will have the same mask requirements at football games as they do while attending school. This means masks will be required at all times for students in grades 4-12 and encouraged for those below 4th grade.

For other guests, once inside the gates, masks will not be required for those who stand around the track area and for those who choose to sit in the north half of the bleachers. These areas will be set aside as mask-optional.

The south half of our bleachers will be set aside as mask-required.

In order to access the concessions and restroom areas, face masks will be required.

Those with a note from a medical doctor exempting them from wearing a face mask will not be required to wear one.

If you have questions or concerns, please contact the school at (712) 568-2020 so they can be addressed. Thank you

post_text:
Free Breakfast & Lunch for all Akron-Westfield Students!

Starting Monday, September 14, 2020, the United States Department of Agriculture has granted the State of Iowa a waiver to operate under the summer program guidelines, allowing all enrolled students to receive free breakfast and lunch regardless of financial status. No application is needed.

This waiver will last until December 31, 2020 unless the federal funding for the program runs out before this date. In the event funding does run out prior to December 31, families will be notified by the school to allow time to make financial adjustments.

If students get any extras beyond the normal tray or if they select items from the a la carte menu, those are not covered under the waiver and would need to be paid for as usual.

Dear Westerner Families,

We were made aware today that someone in the school tested positive for COVID-19. In working with county health officials and our local school nurse, we have identified any individuals who had Close Contact, which is being within 6 feet for 15 minutes or more of the person who tested positive.

All of the individuals affected by this have been informed and families of any students impacted have been notified. If you have not been contacted, that means your student is not affected by this situation.

At this point, school will continue to be offered in-person as we have since the start of the year. Additionally, this situation will not have an impact on any current school activities.

If you have any questions or concerns, please contact the school at (712) 568-2020.

Thank you

post_text:
Tomorrow evening is our first home high school volleyball event for the year. The new bleachers for the high school gymnasium are not due to be installed for a few more weeks, so we will play contests in the elementary gym.

Please note that we will be requiring face masks upon entry to the building and throughout the event. Those with a note from a medical doctor exempting them from wearing a face mask will not be required to wear one.

Face masks may be removed when eating, but all food must be consumed in the commons area. Food will not be allowed in the gym. Beverages will be allowed in the gym and may be consumed in this location as well.

We appreciate your understanding and support as we work diligently to stay in school and to continue to hold as many events as possible.

If you have questions or concerns, please contact the school at (712) 568-2020 so they can be addressed. Thank you

Football Scrimmage Update - Livestream Only - No Fans:

Due to rising concerns with infection rate of COVID-19 in our area, we have decided that we will use our Facebook Page to live stream the football scrimmage tomorrow night against Unity Christian. Fans will not be able to attend in person as we are concerned about the spread of the virus.

Please know that this was a difficult decision but we feel it is the best, under the circumstances. Our ultimate goal is to be in school and stay in school, while also being able to hold all of the activities we normally do. We believe this will give us the best chance of doing that.

As always, we appreciate your support and understanding.

Thank you

Dear Westerners in grades 9-12,

On Friday, the Iowa High School Athletic Association declared their plans to move forward with football for this fall.

If you are interested in being part of the cheer squad for football, please call (712) 568-2020 between 8:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. to get on the list and share your contact information.

We would ask that you please contact us by Friday, August 7 to express interest in cheering so we can be prepared to begin practices some time during the week of August 10.

Since we were unable to hold tryouts in the spring, we are inviting all interested students to join us for practices. Once we begin practices, we will determine the best way to decide who will cheer at varsity contests.

Thank you.

post_text:
Information on Athletic Physicals

If you have a student who will be in grades 7-12 this year and plans to participate in activities that require a physical, please know that Governor Reynolds provided guidance regarding this in her most recent proclamation.

Students who had a physical completed on or after July 1, 2019 will be allowed to utilize that physical for activities through December 31, 2020. Usually physicals can only be utilized for a year at a time.

The Parent Permission and Concussion form that typically accompanies the physical forms we hand out will need to be signed by the parent/guardian and the student just as it has in previous years, so there is no extension for this form.

Please contact the school at (712) 568-2020 should you have any questions about this.

post_text:
Two School Computers for Sale:

Akron-Westfield Schools has two MacBook Pro computers for sale to the public. The market value of each computer is $100, which is the price we are charging.

If you have an interest in purchasing one, please call the school by 4:00 p.m. on Monday, June 1 at (712) 568-2020.

Please call between 8:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. today, tomorrow, or Monday, to get your name on the list. Please note: posts or responses connected to this post will not get your name on the list, so please be sure to call the office if you are interested.

If we have more than two who are interested in purchasing a computer, two names will be randomly drawn at 4:00 p.m. on Monday, June 1.

post_text:
This afternoon, Governor Kim Reynolds announced an extension of school closures through April 30. As a result, Akron-Westfield Schools will continue to be closed through that date.

As we have over the past couple of weeks, we will continue to provide meal services and optional, supplementary learning opportunities for students. More details about how this will look and possibly change will be shared in the coming days.

Many decisions will be made over the coming days and weeks involving a wide range of topics and activities that span all grade levels. Please know that as we determine how we are going to handle each situation, guidance will be provided on Facebook and Remind.

Thank you for your patience and please continue to follow the state's guidance in regard to social distancing. We miss seeing everyone and the more we follow the guidance we are given, the greater chance we have of getting back to school. Thank you.

post_text:
Our teachers have been compiling learning opportunities for students while we are away from school as a result of COVID-19.

To access this information, please go to our school's homepage at: www.akron-westfield.com

Once there, click on the link on the left side entitled "Student Academic Resources".

After following that link, scroll down and you will find additional links for specific grade levels or teachers. Each is set up with this central hub where resources can be accessed and teachers are able to add items to their sites as they wish.

Please keep in mind that the state of Iowa does not allow us to offer an e-learning environment where the work can be assigned and graded. We cannot give credit or extra credit for any work completed, we can only offer supplemental opportunities for students and families to utilize voluntarily.

post_text:
This just in - thank you to Mandy McCully and Tina Milbrodt for their persistence in getting our application approved in an expedited manner, allowing us to provide our daily meals to anyone ages 0 - 18 at no cost to the district while we are out of school!

We just found out that we have been approved and wanted to thank those who have donated to this cause. The funds collected will help cover our transportation costs for making deliveries, which are not covered by this program.

Any remaining funds after we are back in school will go to support our backpack program, a much-needed service that provides food for students on the weekend.

We are fortunate to be in a school district that has so much support for our children from the communities we serve. Thank you to all who have given to make sure all of our children have something healthy to eat at this difficult time.

Huge shoutout to those staff who made this possible!!

Update - Individual Speech State Competition:

The State Speech competition that was scheduled for tomorrow in Carroll, IA, has been cancelled. Additionally, the All-State Speech Festival that was scheduled for March 30 has been cancelled.

In place of this event, A-W will be hiring state-certified speech judges and we will hold our own event at our school.

We have tentatively set a date of Thursday, March 26 for this event. The event will be held in the evening in the auditorium and specific time will be shared once it has been set.

We are proud to announce that Mr. Kent Johnson, high school Social Studies teacher and coach of multiple sports, has been selected by the IGHSAU as this year's Character Counts Coach of the Year. Here is a link to a segment KTIV presented last night during their newscast: https://ktiv.com/2020/03/02/akron-westfields-johnson-wins-character-counts-award/

Mr. Johnson will be recognized this Friday night in Des Moines during half-time of the 3A championship game. He exemplifies the six pillars of Character Counts: Trustworthiness, Respect, Responsibility, Fairness, Caring, and Citizenship.

This award is presented jointly by The Robert D. and Billie Ray Center, the Iowa Sports Foundation (Iowa Games), and the Iowa Girls' High School Athletic Union. In addition to the award, Mr. Johnson will also be presented with a $1,000 check to be used by the A-W athletic department to help promote character development and character education.

On Saturday night in Des Moines, Doug Manley, a 1979 graduate of Akron High School, was one of two individuals selected to lead the Grand March of state place winners at the state wrestling tournament. A prestigious honor given only to those who have consistently dedicated their efforts to promote the sport of wrestling.

Doug is pictured here on the left, leading in this year's state place winners in front of about 17,000 fans. Also pictured is his older daughter, Kayla Bruget, wearing Doug's warm up top from the year he was a state place winner.

Mr. Manley has served Akron-Westfield in a number of capacities over the years, most notably as a school board member. His work to promote the sport of wrestling has included efforts at the state and national levels, helping to develop young officials and provide opportunities for young, developing, athletes, to compete against the best competition.

Congratulations, Doug, on this great honor, it is well deserved.
